--- !u!114 &153596420
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 153596413}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 31629047cadc70941a4f1725fe6382fe, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::CelestialBody
  bodyName: Mars
  labelColor: {r: 1, g: 0.3372549, b: 0, a: 1}
  profileImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: d84684845c6ddc949bd85910a6de6590, type: 3}
  profileDescription: <b>Mars, the fourth planet from the Sun</b>, is known as the
    <b>Red Planet</b> due to its striking reddish appearance. This terrestrial world
    has fascinated humanity for centuries with its polar ice caps, towering volcanoes,
    and intriguing landscapes.\n\nNamed after the Roman god of war, Mars is a prime
    focus of planetary exploration, as scientists search for clues about its climate,
    geological history, and potential for past life.
  stats:
  - label: Mass
    value: <b>6.42 x 10<sup>23</sup>kg</b>
  - label: Diameter
    value: <b>6,792 km</b>
  - label: Distance to Sun
    value: <b>228 million km</b>
  - label: Orbital Period
    value: <b>687 days</b>
  - label: Length of Day
    value: <b>24.7 hours</b>
  - label: Gravity
    value: <b>3,70 m/s<sup>2</sup></b>
  - label: Satellite count
    value: 2
  - label: Temperature (mean)
    value: "<b>-65 \xB0C</b>"
  - label: Atmosphere
    value: CO2
  orbitCharacteristicsDescription: <b>Mars orbits the Sun</b> at an average distance
    of about 228 million kilometers (142 million miles), making it the fourth planet
    in the Solar System. It takes about 687 Earth days to complete one orbit around
    the Sun, resulting in Martian years that are nearly twice as long as those on
    Earth.\n\nMars rotates on its axis approximately every 24.6 hours, meaning that
    a Martian day (or ""sol"") is very similar in length to a day on Earth. The planet's
    highly elliptical orbit contributes to its notable seasonal changes and temperature
    swings.
  structureDescription: <b>Mars has a partially molten iron-sulfur core</b>, which
    is smaller and cooler than Earth's, making it unable to generate a global magnetic
    field.\n\nSurrounding the core is a silicate mantle that was likely geologically
    active in the past, fueling massive volcanic features such as Olympus Mons, the
    largest volcano in the Solar System.\n\nMars's crust, which averages about 50
    kilometers (31 miles) thick, is composed mainly of basaltic rock and is heavily
    marked by impact craters, valleys, and evidence of ancient river channels. This
    crust is rigid and lacks plate tectonics, preserving surface features for billions
    of years.
  atmosphereImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 7ae96ea3af9e15e47b0930f6fa55d829, type: 3}
  atmosphereDescription: "<b>Mars's thin atmosphere</b> is composed primarily of
    carbon dioxide (95%), with small amounts of nitrogen and argon. Because of its
    low density, the atmosphere does little to retain heat, leading to drastic temperature
    variations. Surface temperatures can range from -125\xB0C (-195\xB0F) at the
    poles in winter to a mild 20\xB0C (68\xB0F) near the equator during the day.\\n\\nMars
    experiences seasonal dust storms, some of which can envelope the entire planet
    and obscure its surface for weeks at a time."
  focusDistanceOverride: 0
  minFocusDistanceOverride: 0
  maxFocusDistanceOverride: 30
  galleryEntries: []
