--- !u!114 &581391146
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 581391139}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 31629047cadc70941a4f1725fe6382fe, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::CelestialBody
  bodyName: Mercury
  labelColor: {r: 0.53333336, g: 0.53333336, b: 0.53333336, a: 1}
  profileImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: bc0117e9f38b06943a24622f176707de, type: 3}
  profileDescription: <b>Mercury, the smallest and innermost planet,</b> orbits the
    Sun faster than any other planet, completing a full lap in just 88 days. Named
    after the Roman messenger god, it moves at an average distance of 57.9 million
    kilometers (36 million miles) from the Sun and endures the most intense solar
    radiation in the Solar System. \n \nAs a terrestrial planet, Mercury has a rocky,
    heavily cratered surface with extensive cliffs, or "rupes," from ancient tectonic
    activity. Its orbit is highly elliptical, causing varying distances from the
    Sun, and it rotates very slowly, leading to extremely long days and nights.
  stats:
  - label: Mass
    value: <b>3.30 x 10<sup>23</sup> kg</b>
  - label: Diameter
    value: <b>4,879 km</b>
  - label: Distance to Sun
    value: <b>58 million km</b>
  - label: Orbital Period
    value: <b>88 days</b>
  - label: Length of day
    value: <b>176 days</b>
  - label: Gravity
    value: <b>3.70 m/s<sup>2</sup></b>
  - label: Satellite count
    value: <b>0</b>
  - label: Atmosphere
    value: <b>H+He+O</b>
  - label: Temperature (Day)
    value: "<b>427 \xB0C</b>"
  - label: Temperature (Night)
    value: "<b>-173 \xB0C</b>"
  orbitCharacteristicsDescription: <b>Mercury, the closest planet to the Sun</b>,
    has the fastest orbit in the Solar System, completing a full revolution in just
    88 Earth days at an average speed of 47 kilometers per second (29 miles per second).
    Its highly elliptical orbit ranges from 46 million kilometers (28.6 million miles)
    at its closest point to the Sun (perihelion) to 70 million kilometers (43.5 million
    miles) at its farthest (aphelion), causing significant variations in its surface
    temperatures.\n\nMercury's unique rotation is locked in a 3:2 resonance with
    its orbit, meaning it rotates three times for every two orbits, resulting in
    a single day (sunrise to sunrise) that lasts 176 Earth days-twice as long as
    its year.
  structureDescription: <b>Mercury has a large, iron-rich core</b> that accounts
    for about 85% of its radius, making it one of the most core-dominated planets
    in the Solar System. This core is thought to be partially molten, which contributes
    to Mercury's weak magnetic field, a rarity among terrestrial planets.\n\nSurrounding
    the core is a thin silicate mantle, which is less geologically active than Earth's.\n\nThe
    outer crust, also composed of silicate material, has been shaped by billions
    of years of impact events, leaving the planet covered in craters and surface
    features like cliffs, or ""rupes,"" formed as the planet cooled and contracted.
  atmosphereImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 36fce7af1b0c78a46b6c6bb1a736088e, type: 3}
  atmosphereDescription: "<b>Mercury does not have a traditional atmosphere</b>.
    Instead, it has an exosphere-a tenuous layer of particles, including hydrogen,
    helium, oxygen, sodium, and potassium. This exosphere is constantly replenished
    as particles are knocked from the surface by solar radiation and micrometeoroid
    impacts.\\n\\nWith no substantial atmosphere to trap heat, Mercury's temperatures
    fluctuate wildly, from scorching 430\xB0C (800\xB0F) during the day to freezing
    -180\xB0C (-290\xB0F) at night."
  focusDistanceOverride: 0
  minFocusDistanceOverride: 0
  maxFocusDistanceOverride: 30
  galleryEntries: []
