--- !u!114 &1023854546
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1023854539}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 31629047cadc70941a4f1725fe6382fe, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::CelestialBody
  bodyName: Moon
  labelColor: {r: 0.53333336, g: 0.53333336, b: 0.53333336, a: 1}
  profileImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: d568d86991c861e4485a1b40b1c51fca, type: 3}
  profileDescription: <b>The Moon, Earth's only natural satellite</b>, is known for
    its phases, craters, and influence on Earth's tides, serving as a crucial companion
    since its formation. The Moon orbits Earth at an average distance of 384,400
    kilometers (238,855 miles) and takes about 27.3 days to complete a sidereal orbit.\n\nDue
    to the alignment of the Earth-Moon-Sun system, a full moon cycle, or synodic
    month, lasts about 29.5 days. Tidally locked to Earth, the Moon always shows
    the same side, while the "far side" remains hidden, giving it a consistent face
    in the night sky.
  stats:
  - label: Mass
    value: <b>7.30 x 10<sup>22</sup>kg</b>
  - label: Diameter
    value: <b>3,475 km</b>
  - label: Distance to Planet
    value: <b>384 thousand km</b>
  - label: Orbital Period
    value: <b>27.3 days</b>
  orbitCharacteristicsDescription: "<b>The Moon follows an elliptical orbit around
    Earth</b> at an average distance of approximately 384,400 km, a journey that
    takes about 27.3 days to complete relative to the stars. This path is notably
    tilted at an angle of 5.1\xB0 relative to Earth's orbit around the Sun, which
    explains why eclipses are rare celestial events rather than monthly occurrences.
    Because the Moon and Earth are gravitationally bound, they actually orbit a shared
    center of mass called the barycenter, a point located about 1,700 km beneath
    Earth\u2019s surface."
  structureDescription: "<b>The Moon's structure</b> is a differentiated body, meaning
    it has a compositionally distinct crust, mantle, and core. Seismic studies reveal
    that this layering formed during the Moon\u2019s initial formation in a massive
    magma ocean event.\\n\\nThe outermost layer, or crust, is highly irregular in
    thickness, averaging about 65 km (40 miles) thick on the side facing Earth, but
    much thinner on the lunar farside. It is composed primarily of anorthosite rock,
    rich in oxygen, silicon, and aluminum.\\n\\nBeneath the crust lies the rigid
    and solid mantle, which is about 620 miles (1,000 km) thick. Unlike Earth's,
    the lunar mantle is composed of rocks richer in iron and magnesium (olivine and
    pyroxene) and is not as hot or fluid.\\n\\nAt the very center is a small, dense,
    partially-molten metallic core with a radius of only about 150 miles (240 km).
    It is thought to be made primarily of iron and nickel, and is the reason the
    Moon has such a weak internal magnetic field. The core's relative size (only
    1% to 2% of the Moon's total mass) is much smaller than Earth's or any of the
    other terrestrial planets.\\n\\nThe Moon is entirely geologically inactive, with
    no plate tectonics or current volcanic activity."
  atmosphereImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 45711dc0545115c4c92c8de03730665a, type: 3}
  atmosphereDescription: "<b>The moon's atmosphere </b> is mostly an exosphere, which
    itself is mostly empty space. If you were to visit the Moon and walk around on
    its surface, you might think it had no atmosphere at all. Molecules around the
    Moon are so few and far between that they travel long distances without running
    into anything, even each other. Earth\u2019s atmosphere, on the other hand, is
    dense and collisional: air molecules are bumping into each other (and interfering
    with each other\u2019s movements) all the time.\\n\\nSince the Moon\u2019s atmosphere
    is not collisional, we can study each chemical component independently. For example,
    some scientists work to understand how water forms and changes on the Moon by
    investigating the behavior of hydrogen atoms in the exosphere. Chemical components
    of the lunar exosphere have their own \u2018cycles\u2019 of movement between
    the ground and the space nearby, and distinct migration patterns from place to
    place on the Moon\u2019s surface.  "
  focusDistanceOverride: 0.19
  minFocusDistanceOverride: 0.05
  maxFocusDistanceOverride: 30
  galleryEntries: []
