--- !u!114 &1082364476
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1082364469}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 31629047cadc70941a4f1725fe6382fe, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::CelestialBody
  bodyName: Jupiter
  labelColor: {r: 0.87843144, g: 0.60784316, b: 0.47058827, a: 1}
  profileImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: b115087bf96294f4a9c3d71b6f7ca8b7, type: 3}
  profileDescription: <b>Jupiter is the fifth planet from the Sun</b> and the largest
    in the Solar System, so massive that it could fit all the other planets inside
    it with room to spare. Known for its striking cloud bands and the Great Red Spot,
    Jupiter is a gas giant with a powerful magnetic field and a dynamic atmosphere.\n\nNamed
    after the king of the Roman gods, Jupiter has fascinated scientists and astronomers
    for centuries.
  stats:
  - label: Mass
    value: <b>1.90 x 10<sup>27</sup>kg</b>
  - label: Diameter
    value: <b>142,984 km</b>
  - label: Distance to Sun
    value: <b>779 million km</b>
  - label: Orbital Period
    value: <b>11.9 years</b>
  - label: Length of Day
    value: <b>9.9 hours</b>
  - label: Gravity
    value: <b>23.10 m/s<sup>2</sup></b>
  - label: Satellite count
    value: 95
  - label: Temperature (mean)
    value: "<b>-110 \xB0C</b>"
  - label: Atmosphere
    value: H2+He
  orbitCharacteristicsDescription: <b>Jupiter is located</b> at an average distance
    of about 778 million kilometers (484 million miles) from the Sun, making it the
    fifth planet in the Solar System. It takes approximately 12 Earth years to complete
    a full orbit around the Sun.\n\nJupiter rotates remarkably quickly on its axis,
    completing one rotation in just under 10 hours, which causes the planet to bulge
    slightly at the equator due to centrifugal forces. This rapid rotation is responsible
    for its intense atmospheric bands and contributes to the formation of its powerful
    storms.
  structureDescription: <b>Jupiter's internal structure</b> is dominated by its immense
    pressure and size, starting with a small, dense core made of rock and heavy elements,
    estimated to be 10-20 times the mass of Earth.\n\nSurrounding the core is a thick
    layer of metallic hydrogen, created under the extreme pressures within Jupiter,
    where hydrogen behaves like a conductive metal. This metallic layer generates
    Jupiter's powerful magnetic field.\n\nAbove this is an outer layer of molecular
    hydrogen and helium, transitioning from a fluid state to the gaseous atmosphere
    that features dynamic storms like the Great Red Spot.
  atmosphereImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: ebc2d44b50756314bab555e90c5cdf70, type: 3}
  atmosphereDescription: <b>Jupiter's atmosphere</b> is composed mainly of hydrogen
    and helium, with trace amounts of methane, ammonia, and water vapor. The planet's
    atmosphere is divided into bands of clouds, creating dark belts and light zones
    due to variations in temperature, composition, and circulation patterns.\n\nJupiter's
    most famous feature, the Great Red Spot, is a colossal storm that has been raging
    for at least 350 years. The storm is large enough to fit several Earths inside
    it and showcases Jupiter's extreme weather patterns, which include intense winds
    reaching up to 640 kilometers per hour (400 miles per hour).
  focusDistanceOverride: 0
  minFocusDistanceOverride: 0
  maxFocusDistanceOverride: 30
  galleryEntries: []
