--- !u!114 &1611050360
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1611050353}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 31629047cadc70941a4f1725fe6382fe, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::CelestialBody
  bodyName: Saturn
  labelColor: {r: 1, g: 0.76470596, b: 0, a: 1}
  profileImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 7f54f8136de64e945b9d8dcddbb27ecf, type: 3}
  profileDescription: <b>Saturn, the sixth planet from the Sun</b>, is the second
    largest in the Solar System and is best known for its magnificent ring system.
    This gas giant, named after the Roman god of agriculture and wealth, has captivated
    astronomers for centuries with its striking rings, numerous moons, and unique
    atmosphere.\n\nSaturn's immense size, complex system, and visual beauty make
    it one of the most iconic planets in our Solar System.
  stats:
  - label: Mass
    value: <b>5.68 x 10<sup>26</sup>kg</b>
  - label: Diameter
    value: <b>120,536 km</b>
  - label: Distance to Sun
    value: <b>1,432 million km</b>
  - label: Orbital Period
    value: <b>29 years</b>
  - label: Length of Day
    value: <b>10.7 hours</b>
  - label: Gravity
    value: <b>9 m/s<sup>2</sup></b>
  - label: Satellite count
    value: 146
  - label: Temperature (mean)
    value: "<b>-140 \xB0C</b>"
  - label: Atmosphere
    value: H2+He
  orbitCharacteristicsDescription: <b>Saturn orbits the Sun</b> at an average distance
    of about 1.4 billion kilometers (886 million miles), making it the sixth planet
    from the Sun. It takes Saturn approximately 29.5 Earth years to complete one
    orbit.\n\nSaturn rotates rapidly on its axis, with a day lasting only about 10.7
    hours. This rapid rotation, combined with its low density, causes Saturn to have
    an oblate shape, with noticeable flattening at the poles and a bulging equator.
  structureDescription: <b>Saturn has a central rocky core</b>, similar to Jupiter's
    but less massive, surrounded by a thick layer of metallic hydrogen formed under
    immense pressure. This metallic layer generates a magnetic field, though weaker
    than Jupiter's.\n\nAbove it lies a layer of molecular hydrogen, which transitions
    smoothly into the gaseous outer atmosphere. Saturn's lower density compared to
    Jupiter reflects its smaller size and weaker gravitational compression.\n\nThe
    atmosphere is primarily hydrogen and helium, with trace amounts of methane and
    ammonia, contributing to the planet's subtle yellowish hue.
  atmosphereImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: baec1d1dc89dad146b5ee41a768bb640, type: 3}
  atmosphereDescription: <b>Saturn's atmosphere</b> is mostly hydrogen and helium,
    with trace amounts of methane, ammonia, and water vapor. Its upper atmosphere
    is divided into cloud bands and zones, creating subtle stripes similar to Jupiter's,
    though less distinct./n/nSaturn experiences fierce storms and powerful winds,
    with speeds reaching up to 1,800 kilometers per hour (1,100 miles per hour) near
    the equator. One of its most fascinating atmospheric features is a long-lasting
    hexagonal storm at its north pole, with a distinctive six-sided shape that scientists
    are still studying.
  focusDistanceOverride: 2
  minFocusDistanceOverride: 0.8
  maxFocusDistanceOverride: 30
  galleryEntries: []
