--- !u!114 &1928992226
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1928992219}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 31629047cadc70941a4f1725fe6382fe, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::CelestialBody
  bodyName: Uranus
  labelColor: {r: 0, g: 0.7843138, b: 1, a: 1}
  profileImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: ef23a8ac8b151af4d9093293a1ff93e7, type: 3}
  profileDescription: <b>Uranus, the seventh planet from the Sun</b>, is known for
    its striking blue-green color and unique sideways tilt. As one of the two ice
    giants in the Solar System, along with Neptune, Uranus has a composition and
    atmosphere distinct from the gas giants, Jupiter and Saturn.\n\nDiscovered in
    the late 18th century, Uranus remains a mysterious world due to its distance
    from Earth.
  stats:
  - label: Mass
    value: <b>8.68 x 10<sup>25</sup>kg</b>
  - label: Diameter
    value: <b>51,118 km</b>
  - label: Distance to Sun
    value: <b>2,867 million km</b>
  - label: Orbital Period
    value: <b>84 years</b>
  - label: Length of Day
    value: <b>17.2 hours</b>
  - label: Gravity
    value: <b>8.70m/s<sup>2</sup></b>
  - label: Satellite count
    value: 28
  - label: Temperature (mean)
    value: "<b>-195 \xB0C</b>"
  - label: Atmosphere
    value: H2+He
  orbitCharacteristicsDescription: <b>Uranus orbits the Sun</b> at an average distance
    of approximately 2.9 billion kilometers (1.8 billion miles), making it the seventh
    planet from the Sun. It takes about 84 Earth years to complete a single orbit,
    meaning each Uranian season lasts over 20 Earth years.\n\nUranus's most unusual
    feature is its extreme axial tilt of about 98 degrees, which causes the planet
    to rotate on its side. This sideways tilt leads to extreme seasonal changes,
    with each pole facing the Sun continuously for about 42 Earth years before switching.\n\nA
    day on Uranus, defined as the time it takes to complete one rotation on its axis,
    lasts about 17 hours and 14 minutes.
  structureDescription: <b>Uranus's internal structure</b> begins with a small rocky
    core, composed of silicates and metals, which is surrounded by a thick mantle
    of water, ammonia, and methane ""ices."" This icy mantle accounts for the majority
    of Uranus's mass and gives it its classification as an ice giant.\n\nThe outer
    layer consists of molecular hydrogen and helium, with trace amounts of methane
    that give Uranus its pale blue-green color.\n\nUnlike gas giants, Uranus lacks
    a metallic hydrogen layer, and its tilted axis creates unique seasonal variations
    in its outer atmospheric and internal processes.
  atmosphereImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: ea734cf4efe8d7144bbab155d73436d9, type: 3}
  atmosphereDescription: "<b>The atmosphere of Uranus</b> is composed mainly of hydrogen
    and helium, with traces of methane and other hydrocarbons. Methane, which gives
    Uranus its distinctive color, absorbs red light and reflects blue and green wavelengths.
    The atmosphere is layered, with an upper cloud layer made of methane ice, and
    possibly deeper layers of water and ammonia clouds.\\n\\nAlthough Uranus has
    relatively few visible features compared to other planets, seasonal changes have
    been observed in its cloud formations. Temperatures in Uranus's upper atmosphere
    drop as low as -224\xB0C (-371\xB0F), making it one of the coldest planets in
    the Solar System."
  focusDistanceOverride: 0
  minFocusDistanceOverride: 0
  maxFocusDistanceOverride: 30
  galleryEntries: []
